A JWT (JSON Web Token) is a secure token used to authenticate users between client and server 
without storing session data on the server. It is widely used
 in APIs (FastAPI, Django, React apps, mobile apps, microservices)—so it’s very useful 
 for your backend projects like your AI voice agent or autodialer dashboards where secure API access is required.

What is JWT (simple explanation)

Think of JWT like a digital ID card.
Example flow:

User logs in with username/password
Server verifies credentials
Server creates a JWT token
Client stores token
Client sends token with every request
Server verifies token → allows access

No need to store session on server → stateless authentication.

Structure of JWT

JWT has 3 parts

HEADER.PAYLOAD.SIGNATURE
1️⃣ Header

Contains algorithm info
Example:
{
 "alg": "HS256",
 "typ": "JWT"
}

2️⃣ Payload
Contains user data (called claims)
Example:
{
 "user_id": 101,
 "role": "admin",
 "exp": 1712345678
}

3️⃣ Signature
Used to verify token authenticity
If someone changes payload → signature becomes invalid.
Where JWT is used
Common real-world uses:
Login authentication
Secure APIs
Role-based dashboards
Microservices communication
Mobile apps
Single Page Applications

Example:
Your FastAPI backend → issues JWT
Frontend dashboard → sends token in requests


